oxc-project/javascript-globals#149.body:
Oxlint repeatedly looks up `GLOBALS["builtin"]` in some rules. PHF lookups are not so cheap, so it'd be ideal to avoid doing these lookups repeatedly.

That would be possible if this crate also exported a `static` for each environment.

```rs
type Env = phf::Map<&'static str, bool>;

// Individual envs
pub static GLOBALS_BUILTIN: Env = phf::Map { /* ... */ };
pub static GLOBALS_ES2026: Env = phf::Map { /* ... */ };
// ... etc ...

// Same as now
pub static GLOBALS: phf::Map<&'static str, Env> = phf::Map { /* ... */ };
```

Generating the separate `GLOBALS_*` definitions is simple. The part which is not quite so trivial is defining the main `GLOBALS` static so that it references the same data as the individual env statics, and doesn't duplicate the data twice.

Something like this might work:

```rs
const fn clone_env(env: &Env) -> Env {
    phf::Map { key: env.key, disps: env.disps, entries: env.entries }
}

pub static GLOBALS: phf::Map<&'static str, Env> = phf::Map {
    // Generated by phf codegen
    key: 16263683158343804936,
    disps: &[
        (0, 1),
        (5, 11),
        (3, 5),
        (21, 41),
        (0, 0),
        (0, 0),
        (10, 15),
        (0, 11),
        (18, 22),
    ],
    // Custom generated
    entries: &[
        ("builtin", clone_env(&GLOBALS_BUILTIN)),
        ("es2026", clone_env(&GLOBALS_ES2026)),
        // ... etc ...
    ],
};
```

`disps` and `entries` fields of `phf::Map` are both `&'static [T]` slices, so this *should* avoid duplicating the data, and just reference it in 2 places.

