oxc-project/oxc#15325.body:
When using JS plugins that wrap the `context` object (like `eslint-plugin-mozilla`), accessing `context.sourceCode` from the wrapped context throws a `TypeError: Cannot read private member #internal from an object whose class did not declare it`.

This breaks compatibility with ESLint plugins that create wrapper rules by copying or proxying the context object.

## Reproduction

The issue occurs when a plugin rule wraps another rule and passes a modified context. Here's a minimal reproduction:

```typescript
// Plugin that wraps another rule (simulates eslint-plugin-mozilla pattern)
const baseRule = {
  create(context) {
    const sourceCode = context.sourceCode; // This will fail
    return { /* visitor */ };
  },
};

const wrappingRule = {
  create(context) {
    // Create wrapped context by copying properties
    const wrappedContext = Object.create(Object.getPrototypeOf(context));
    for (const key of Object.keys(context)) {
      wrappedContext[key] = context[key];
    }

    // Pass wrapped context to base rule
    return baseRule.create(wrappedContext); // Error occurs here
  },
};
```

**Config:**
```json
{
  "jsPlugins": ["eslint-plugin-mozilla"],
  "rules": {
    "mozilla/no-redeclare-with-import-autofix": "error"
  }
}
```

## Error Output

```
x Error running JS plugin.
| File path: /path/to/file.js
| TypeError: Cannot read private member #internal from an object whose class did not declare it
|     at getInternal (file:///path/to/oxlint/dist/plugins.js:9242:29)
|     at get sourceCode (file:///path/to/oxlint/dist/plugins.js:9193:3)
```

## Root Cause

The `Context` class in `apps/oxlint/src-js/plugins/context.ts` uses a private field `#internal` to store internal data:

```typescript
export class Context {
  #internal: InternalContext;

  get sourceCode(): SourceCode {
    getInternal(this, 'access `context.sourceCode`');
    return SOURCE_CODE;
  }
}
```

The `getInternal` function accesses `context.#internal`:

```typescript
getInternal = (context, actionDescription) => {
  const internal = context.#internal; // Fails if context is not original instance
  if (internal.ruleIndex === -1) throw new Error(...);
  return internal;
};
```

When a plugin wraps the context object (even using `Object.create(Object.getPrototypeOf(context))`), the private `#internal` field is not preserved. Private class fields are not enumerable and cannot be copied through property enumeration or prototype chains.

This is a common pattern in ESLint plugins:
- **eslint-plugin-mozilla**: Rules like `no-redeclare-with-import-autofix` wrap ESLint's core `no-redeclare` rule
- Other plugins may proxy or extend contexts to override methods like `report()`

## Affected Plugins

- `eslint-plugin-mozilla` (confirmed)
- Potentially any plugin that wraps or extends context objects

oxc-project/oxc#15508.body:
### What version of Oxlint are you using?

1.26.0

### What command did you run?

`oxlint -c .oxlintrc.json`

### What does your `.oxlintrc.json` config file look like?

```jsonc
{
  "$schema": "./node_modules/oxlint/configuration_schema.json",
  "plugins": [
    "react"
  ],
  "rules": {
    "react/jsx-filename-extension": [
      "error",
      {
        "extensions": [
          // baz.tsx would trigger this lint error right now even though it should not, because `tsx` does not have a `.` at the start of it.
          ".jsx",
          "tsx"
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```


### What happened?

One works and the other does not.

The original ESLint rule is checking the extension like so:
`const isAllowedExtension = allowedExtensions.some((extension) => filename.slice(-extension.length) === extension);`

Which is why that worked for ESLint, `.jsx` grabs the last 4 characters of the filename, `jsx` grabs the last 3 characters, and thus either way it passes as long as the file has an acceptable extension. In oxc, it only works for extensions with `.` at the start.

```rs
let extensions = config
    .and_then(|v| v.get("extensions"))
    .and_then(Value::as_array)
    .map(|v| {
        v.iter()
            .filter_map(serde_json::Value::as_str)
            // filter to only
            // this (silently) only considers extensions that start with a dot, different behavior from eslint
            .filter(|&s| s.starts_with('.'))
            .map(|s| &s[1..])
            .map(CompactStr::from)
            .collect()
    })
    .unwrap_or(vec![CompactStr::from("jsx")]);
```

I noticed this issue because of Mastodon having `tsx` as [a config option on this lint rule in their eslint config](https://github.com/mastodon/mastodon/blob/6337e036f3bc5ece013d5b2536d7d16b1ec658e8/eslint.config.mjs#L272-L277).

Solution: Make this work the same with either `.tsx` or `tsx`. Omitting/including the dot should not matter.

