### What does your `.oxlintrc.json` config file look like?

```jsonc
{
  "$schema": "./node_modules/oxlint/configuration_schema.json",
  "plugins": [
    "eslint"
  ],
  "categories": {
    "correctness": "off"
  },
  "rules": {
    "no-console": "error"
  }
}
```


### What happened?

Basically, when a file is a node script with a `#!/usr/bin/env node` as the first line, applying the quick fix for "disable rule for whole file" creates an invalid file. If we have a hashbang line, we should apply the `oxlint-disable` on the second line of the file.

I have a reproduction repro here: https://github.com/connorshea/oxlint-disable-directive-issue-repro

Reproduction steps:

- `git clone https://github.com/connorshea/oxlint-disable-directive-issue-repro`
- `cd oxlint-disable-directive-issue-repro`
- `npm install`
- Open the repo in VS Code (or another LSP-based editor that supports quick fixes)
- Open `index.js`, which looks like this:

```js
#!/usr/bin/env node

// If I try to apply the "disable rule for whole file" fix here,
// it will go to the top of the file. I want to keep the
// `#!/usr/bin/env node` line as the first thing in the file
// so the file is valid.
console.log("this isn't allowed :)");
```

On the `console.log` line, there is a diagnostic which can be quick-fixed:

<img width="773" height="348" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c65147d4-c927-4f1f-8428-83d59a3bbf54" />

If you fix it by applying the "disable no-console for this whole file" quick fix, the result is this code, which is invalid:

```js
// oxlint-disable no-console
#!/usr/bin/env node

// If I try to apply the "disable rule for whole file" fix here,
// it will go to the top of the file. I want to keep the
// `#!/usr/bin/env node` line as the first thing in the file
// so the file is valid.
console.log("this isn't allowed :)");
```

oxc-project/oxc#17584.body:
Hello (and happy new year),

I'm having a problem with oxlint auto-fix feature on class constructor linting.

The sample code is something like:

```ts
@injectable()
export class SomeRepository extends Repository<SomeModel> {
  constructor(@inject(SomeModel) model: SomeModel) {
    super(model)
  }
}
```

...for which running oxlint in fix mode removes the constructor entirely.

i do understand that a constructor with a single super() call is something which we could normally optimize (= 100% remove) **but not here** since it has a decorator used for dependency injection.

i think it's kind of an edge case, because i think people using DI are not the majority, therefore i think it could be a bug of a case not handled yet. i wish i could help but i don't master rust and i don't think proposing a claude PR would help (but i could be wrong and i'd be happy to try if you agreed to it)

please let me know what can be done 🙏

oxc-project/oxc#17598.body:
## Description

When using `oxc-transform`'s isolated declarations feature (`typescript.declaration: true`), default values in rest parameters are incorrectly preserved in the generated `.d.ts` files. This causes TypeScript compiler errors when these declaration files are consumed, as parameter initializers are not allowed in declaration files.

## Environment

- **oxc-transform version**: Latest (as of 2026-01-02)
- **TypeScript version**: 5.x
- **tsconfig.json**: `isolatedDeclarations: true`

## Reproduction

### Source Code (`dateTime.ts`)

```typescript
export function formatDate(
  config: {
    locale: string;
    timeZone?: string;
  },
  getDateTimeFormat: SomeType,
  ...[value, options = {}]: Parameters<SomeFormatter['formatDate']>
): string {
  // implementation
}
```

### oxc-transform Configuration

```javascript
import { transformSync } from 'oxc-transform';

const result = transformSync(filePath, code, {
  lang: 'ts',
  sourcemap: false,
  typescript: {
    onlyRemoveTypeImports: true,
    declaration: true,
  },
});

// result.declaration contains the generated .d.ts
```

### Generated Declaration File (Incorrect)

```typescript
export declare function formatDate(
  config: {
    locale: string;
    timeZone?: string;
  },
  getDateTimeFormat: SomeType,
  ...[value, options = {}]: Parameters<SomeFormatter["formatDate"]>
): string;
```

### Expected Declaration File (Correct)

```typescript
export declare function formatDate(
  config: {
    locale: string;
    timeZone?: string;
  },
  getDateTimeFormat: SomeType,
  ...args: Parameters<SomeFormatter["formatDate"]>
): string;
```

Or better yet, the rest parameter should be expanded:

```typescript
export declare function formatDate(
  config: {
    locale: string;
    timeZone?: string;
  },
  getDateTimeFormat: SomeType,
  value: Parameters<SomeFormatter["formatDate"]>[0],
  options?: Parameters<SomeFormatter["formatDate"]>[1]
): string;
```

## Error

When consuming the generated `.d.ts` file, TypeScript reports:

```
error TS2371: A parameter initializer is only allowed in a function or constructor implementation.
```

## Impact

This bug prevents using oxc-transform's isolated declarations feature as a drop-in replacement for `tsc --emitDeclarationOnly` when the source code contains rest parameters with default values.

## Workaround

The only workaround is to modify the source code to avoid rest parameter syntax with defaults:

```typescript
// Instead of:
...[value, options = {}]: Parameters<SomeFormatter['formatDate']>

// Use explicit parameters:
value: Parameters<SomeFormatter['formatDate']>[0],
options: Parameters<SomeFormatter['formatDate']>[1] = {}
```

## Context

This issue was discovered while migrating a large monorepo ([formatjs](https://github.com/formatjs/formatjs)) to use oxc-transform for both JavaScript transpilation and declaration generation. The rest parameter pattern with defaults is relatively common in TypeScript codebases.

## Related

- TypeScript's `isolatedDeclarations` mode should not preserve implementation details like default values in declaration files
- The rest parameter syntax is a convenient way to maintain type safety with variadic functions
- This affects any TypeScript project using isolated declarations with oxc-transform

## Expected Behavior

oxc-transform's isolated declarations should either:
1. Strip default values from rest parameters in generated `.d.ts` files, OR
2. Expand rest parameters into individual parameters without default values in the declaration

---

**Sources:**
- [oxc-transform npm package](https://www.npmjs.com/package/oxc-transform)
- [Oxc Transformer Alpha announcement](https://oxc.rs/blog/2024-09-29-transformer-alpha)
- [TypeScript Transformer docs](https://oxc.rs/docs/guide/usage/transformer/typescript)

