oxc-project/oxc#17912.body:
This rule has a fixer, but it should probably be a suggestion (and maybe even dangerous?): https://github.com/oxc-project/oxc/blob/c778cba9d5e828b7d021fe32297e798954e35575/crates/oxc_linter/src/rules/vitest/no_import_node_test.rs

The fixer makes changes like this:

```js
// Before
import { test } from "node:test";
// After
import { test } from "vitest";
```

But there's no check for what the import is / whether the imported modules exist in both node:test and vitest. As such, you can end up with an invalid import due to this rule in some cases.

oxc-project/oxc#17927.body:
I encountered a false positive in `eslint(no-unused-vars)` where a namespace is flagged as unused if it is shadowed by a generic type parameter in a function signature, even though the namespace is explicitly used in the type constraint.

This is a confirmed bug in upstream `typescript-eslint`: **[Issue #10746](https://github.com/typescript-eslint/typescript-eslint/issues/10746)**.

Oxc currently faithfully reproduces this buggy behavior.

### Reproduction

**[Oxc Playground Link](https://playground.oxc.rs/#)**

```typescript
namespace Database {
  export type Table<T> = T;
}

// 'Database' generic shadows the namespace, but namespace is used in 'Database.Table'
export function test<Database, Table extends Database.Table<Database>>(
  database: Database,
  table: Table
): { database: Database; table: Table } {
  return { database, table };
}

```

### Actual Behavior

The linter reports `Database` (the namespace) as unused:

```text
  ! eslint(no-unused-vars): Variable 'Database' is declared but never used.
   ,-[:1:11]
 1 | namespace Database {
   :           ^^^^|^^^
   :               `-- 'Database' is declared here
 2 |   export type Table<T> = T;
   `----
  help: Consider removing this declaration.

```

### Expected Behavior

The namespace `Database` should be marked as used because it is accessed in the generic constraint `extends Database.Table<...>`.

### Question regarding Scope

Since this is an upstream bug that Oxc has successfully replicated: **Is the goal here to fix this logic in Oxc to be correct, or is 1:1 compatibility with ESLint (including reproducing their bugs) the priority?**

oxc-project/oxc#17928.body:
Given the below code:


```typescript
namespace Database {
  export type Table<T> = T;
}

// 'Database' generic shadows the namespace, but namespace is used in 'Database.Table'
export function test<Database, Table extends Database.Table<Database>>(
  database: Database,
  table: Table
): { database: Database; table: Table } {
  return { database, table };
}
```

the top level `Database` symbol has no references, this is incorrect as it is refernced in the `extends Database.Table`

```
Database (id: 0): {
  symbol_id: 0
  span: { start: 10, end: 18 }
  name: "Database"
  flags: ValueModule
  scope_id: 0
  references: []
}
```

In typescript the left side of `Database.Table` is resolved with `SymbolFlags.Namespace`

https://github.com/microsoft/typescript/blob/c574e4090d9f428f841d8098aebc302b0187182e/src/compiler/checker.ts#L4529

When TS uses `SymbolFlags.Namespace`, it understands that type parameters have `SymbolFlags.TypeParameter`, and automatically excludes them when resolving the left side of a qualified name.

